Background

In this markdown, I analyze this data of Pokemons.

Goal

The goal of the project is to demonstrate and practice the different elements we have been talking about in the course, which are a part of most data analysis/data science projects.

Here are some related research questions which has been raised during this project that we can examine:

  • What is the difference between a legendary pokemon and other pokemons in thier Total score?

  • What is the relationship between Pokemons that have type 2 and legendariness or sp.atk?

  • Is there a type 1 bias in total score?

  • Does the total score is normaly distributed?

  • Is there a relationship between Generation and Pokemon’s Total score?

  • Is there a difference in Attack between Fire Type Pokemon and Grass Type Pokemon?

We will focus in this two:

Linear Regression: Is there a relation between the Speed and Total score? (Does the Total score depended on the speed?)

Hypothesis test: Null Hypothesis: The average in HP of Bug Type Pokemon is equal to the HP of Flyig Type Pokemon.

Alternative Hypothesis: The average in HP of Bug Type Pokemon is not equal to the HP of Flyig Type Pokemon. \[H_0: \mu_{HP_{bug}}- \mu_{HP_{flying}}=0\] \[H_1: \mu_{HP_{bug}}- \mu_{HP_{flying}}\neq0\]

There exists a weak positive relationship between the Speed and the Attack attributes but a stronger positive linear relationship between HP and the Attack attribute. The legendary Pokemons are labeled on the scatter plot. Most of the legendary pokemons have higher speed and HP than other.

hp_defense_legendary <- ggplot(na.omit(mydata), aes(Defense, HP)) + geom_point(aes(color=Legendary)) + geom_label_repel(data=subset(mydata, (Defense > 150 | Defense < 50 | HP > 150) & Legendary == 1 | HP > 200), aes(label=Name), box.padding = 0.35, point.padding = 0.5, segment.color = 'grey50') + geom_smooth(method = "lm")

Speed has a kind of a weak negative linear relationship to Defense. Speed doesn’t increased as defense increase, which means defensive Pokemon are generally slower than their offensive counterparts. HP has pretty the same behaviour to Defense as to Attack.

The R-Squared is not very high, around 0.33 which means that only 33% of the variation in the dependent variable is explained by the independent variable. But the p-Value is very important because, We can consider a linear model to be statistically significant only when p-Value is less that the statistical significance level, which is 0.05. This is visually interpreted by the significance stars at the end of the row. The more the stars beside the variable’s p-Value, the more significant the variable. Here we can see that there is three stars which is the most significant.

Quantile-quantile (Q-Q) plot is a graphical display to compare a data set to a particular probability distribution or to compare it to another data set. If the data are exactly normal, we expect the points to lie on a straight line. The data we have here are pretty close to lying on a line.

#Hypothesis test: Null Hypothesis: The average in HP of Bug Type Pokemon is equal to the HP of Flyig Type Pokemon. Alternative Hypothesis: The average in HP of Bug Type Pokemon is not equal to the HP of Flyig Type Pokemon.

# creating filtered data which contain the Bug and Flying Types of Pokemons
Bug_Flying_data <- myNewData %>% filter(Type.1 %in%
                                     c("Bug", "Flying"))

# Group by the types with their mean score:
Bug_Flying_data2 <- Bug_Flying_data %>% group_by(Type.1) %>% summarise(mean_score=mean(Total))
Bug_Flying_data2
## # A tibble: 2 x 2
##   Type.1 mean_score
##   <fct>       <dbl>
## 1 Bug          380.
## 2 Flying       485
# Plot this data.
p2 <- ggplot(Bug_Flying_data2, aes(Type.1, mean_score))
p2 + geom_bar(stat="identity")

Let’s do the Hypothesis test We use t-test to determine whether the means of two Types are equal to each other. The assumption for the test is that both groups are sampled from normal distributions with equal variances. The null hypothesis is that the two means are equal, and the alternative is that they are not equal.

To perform two-samples t-test comparing the means of two independent samples (x & y), the R function t.test() can be used as follow:

# R function to compute unpaired two-samples t-test
t.test(x = myNewDataHot$HP[myNewDataHot$Type.1_Bug == "1"], y = myNewDataHot$HP[myNewDataHot$Type.1_Flying == "1"], alternative = "two.sided")
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  myNewDataHot$HP[myNewDataHot$Type.1_Bug == "1"] and myNewDataHot$HP[myNewDataHot$Type.1_Flying == "1"]
## t = -1.2459, df = 3.1923, p-value = 0.2964
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -45.42678  19.24021
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  57.65672  70.75000

The p-value of t-test is p = 0.2964. It’s greater than the significance level alpha = 0.05. In conclusion,we failed to reject that there is no significant difference between the average HP score of the two Types of pokemons. We can also support this due to the confidence interval which results here.
